---
import PageLayout from '../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../data/site';
import { TOPIC_HUBS } from '../data/taxonomy';
---

<PageLayout
  title="About"
  pageTitle="About"
  pageSubtitle="The person behind the publication."
  description="About Nick Miethe — technical executive, architect, and builder writing about AI agents, agentic SDLC, and modern software delivery."
>
  <div class="space-y-10">

    <!-- Bio section -->
    <section class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-8 items-start">
      <div class="shrink-0">
        <div class="flex h-24 w-24 items-center justify-center rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-indigo-500 to-violet-600 text-3xl font-bold text-white overflow-hidden">
          <img src="/assets/1M.png" alt={site.author.name} class="h-full w-full object-cover" />
        </div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--text-primary)] mb-2">{site.author.name}</h2>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-tertiary)] text-sm mb-4">Technical Executive · Architect · Builder</p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
          <a
            href={site.author.social.github}
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border-subtle)] px-3 py-1.5 text-xs font-medium text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:bg-[var(--bg-muted)] transition-colors"
          >
            GitHub
          </a>
          <a
            href={site.author.social.linkedin}
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border-subtle)] px-3 py-1.5 text-xs font-medium text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:bg-[var(--bg-muted)] transition-colors"
          >
            LinkedIn
          </a>
          <a
            href={site.author.social.twitter}
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
            class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border-subtle)] px-3 py-1.5 text-xs font-medium text-[var(--text-secondary)] hover:bg-[var(--bg-muted)] transition-colors"
          >
            Twitter / X
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <!-- Professional background -->
    <section>
      <h2>Who I Am, What I Actually Do</h2>
      <p>
        I'm a technical leader, architect, and builder working at the intersection of enterprise modernization and the emerging agentic SDLC. Most of my paid time goes to being the Chief Architect for the Red Hat practice and the CTO of BoxBoat, both within IBM Consulting Hybrid Cloud & Data: helping organizations migrate from VMware, modernize their delivery platforms, and build the operating models that actually make cloud-native work at scale. A considerable portion of my time is spent on offering development, defining the patterns that we then take to our clients.
      </p>
      <p>
        My path here started in network engineering consulting (Cisco), then software engineering (SAS, Allscripts), and then moved through enterprise container enablement, automation transformation, and eventually into the consulting-leadership layer where architecture decisions meet go-to-market reality. That sequence produced a systems-first bias I haven't been able to shake: I treat "platform," "process," and "people" as three views of the same problem, not three separate workstreams. I also have a long history of internal tools development and optimization; I'm perpetually unable to operate with inefficiencies.
      </p>
      <p>
        Outside client work, I am a hobby developer of software, which is where tools like <strong>CCDash</strong> (session analytics for agent work) and <strong>SkillMeat</strong> (an artifact manager for agentic development) live. These aren't weekend toys; they're the places I test ideas before they show up in client engagements or on this site. I also speak occasionally on OpenShift and platform topics (Red Hat Summit Connect, KubeCon), and right now I'm particularly focused on AI agents as genuine participants in software delivery: not AI-as-autocomplete, but AI as a structural force that changes what accountability, seniority, and SDLC architecture actually mean.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Areas of focus -->
    <section>
      <h2>Areas of Focus</h2>
      <p>My thinking covers seven interconnected domains — each relevant to the technical executive, architect, or senior practitioner:</p>

      <ul>
        {TOPIC_HUBS.map((hub) => (
          <li>
            <strong>
              <a href={`/topics/${hub.slug}/`}>{hub.label}</a>
            </strong>
            {' '}— {hub.description}
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- What to expect -->
    <section>
      <h2>What to Expect from This Publication</h2>
      <p>
        Signal to System is a technical publication, not a blog. The distinction matters:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Long-form over short-form.</strong> I write essays, not listicles. Each piece is designed to develop an argument with enough depth to actually change how you think or build, not just confirm what you already knew.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Practitioner-first.</strong> Everything here emerges from real systems experience — not academic research summaries, not think-pieces divorced from implementation. I'll show my work.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Both the what and the why.</strong> Technical decisions are strategic decisions. I try to surface the organizational, architectural, and epistemic factors that make certain approaches work — not just the mechanics.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Honest about uncertainty.</strong> Where I'm uncertain, I'll say so. Where there's legitimate disagreement, I'll try to represent it fairly before arguing a position.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Structured reading paths.</strong> Because topics connect, I organize content into series and link related pieces. You can follow a thread end-to-end, or graze across topics.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Outside the office -->
    <section>
      <h2>Outside the Office</h2>
      <p>
        A few things that are true and worth knowing, because I don't really separate the "professional" and "personal" lenses all that cleanly:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          Most of the research on this site starts somewhere in my homelab (a Proxmox cluster, Fedora hosts, a macOS box, and more mini-PCs than a responsible adult should admit to). It's where ideas get stress-tested before they make it into client work or a post.
        </li>
        <li>
          I'm a dad of three. A lot of my thinking about learning systems gets sharpened by watching Montessori-aligned pedagogy work (and occasionally not work) in real time at home.
        </li>
        <li>
          I have walls of Ikea Lack shelves full of aspirational board games that I'll eventually play my way through. They share the room with my makerspace: a room full of 3D printers, an electronics lab, drawers of IoT components, and too much more I won't mention.
        </li>
        <li>
          Based in Bermuda Run, NC, with my family and two dogs, Ty and Stanley, who have strong opinions about squirrels.
        </li>
        <li>
          Continuously learning through HBR issues, podcasts, and strategic NotebookLM + Perplexity usage, because the leadership & strategy muscle needs its own reps; ideally without making me sound like a strategy deck.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Speaking / consulting -->
    <section>
      <h2>Speaking, Consulting, and Collaboration</h2>
      <p>
        I occasionally advise organizations on technical strategy, AI agent adoption, and platform engineering. If you're working on something interesting at the intersection of AI systems and software delivery — or if you want to discuss a piece you read here — you can reach me on <a href={site.author.social.linkedin}>LinkedIn</a> or <a href={site.author.social.twitter}>Twitter / X</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Site disclaimer -->
    <section>
      <h2>Disclaimer</h2>
      <p class="text-sm">
        {site.defaultDisclaimer}
      </p>
    </section>

  </div>
</PageLayout>
